Brain size beyond basic capacity does not relate to intelligence as we understand it.  The closest physiological connection I am aware of for intelligence measure is the number of nerve connections bridging the corpus collosum between the two hemispheres of the brain.  Very few are fond in children born handicapped, and far more than average are seen in the profoundly gifted.  Furthermore, brain activity tends to relate to motion and decision processes related to them.  Nerves feed back so that we can act.  Aside from rotating leaves to face light, I am not aware of a significant plant population that twitches (quick, someone mention the venus flytrap!)<br>
